From f6834ea606e6991fc845517a3642dbed1b84a9e0 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Capivara CI <ci@capivara.dev>
Date: Sat, 27 Jun 2026 20:59:11 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] host: store VirtioGpuFrontend::mResources as shared_ptr,
 guard map ops with a mutex

mResources is reached from the dispatch thread (holding the Rust-side
Arc<Mutex<VirtioGpu>>), a deferred TransferFromHost3d reader thread
(deliberately NOT holding that lock -- see
rutabaga_gfx::transfer_read_blocking_by_id), and potentially any of
gfxstream's own SyncThread worker-pool threads running a fence/compose
completion callback. None of those call sites share a single lock
today, so a VirtioGpuResource stored by value could be erased or
move-assigned out from under an in-flight reader, leaving its
mIovs/mLinear dangling.

Changes mResources to map to shared_ptr<VirtioGpuResource> and adds
mResourcesMutex, held only around the map operation itself (find/
insert/erase), never across any blocking I/O. A caller copies the
shared_ptr under the lock, releases it immediately, then does its
(possibly slow) work through that copy -- the resource stays alive
for as long as any copy of the shared_ptr does, even if another
thread erases it from the map in the meantime. This is deadlock-free
by construction: the lock is never held across the long pipe wait
TransferRead can do, so it can't reintroduce the dispatcher deadlock
libkrun 0007 exists to avoid.

This is a real, independently-justified structural fix for a genuine
class of bug (map-level use-after-free), found while investigating the
SIGSEGV in TransferWithIov tracked since libkrun 0010. It is NOT
confirmed to be sufficient on its own: the exact same crash, with the
exact same corrupted bytes, reproduced again after this change (see
the capivara-compose-loop-blocker memory note). The corrupted address
decodes to a literal substring of a Capivara-side string constant
("/tmp/capy-adb-5555.sock"), which doesn't fit a classic cross-thread
data race (those produce varying garbage, not byte-identical garbage
across unrelated sessions) -- pointing instead at a deterministic
logic bug, likely an iovec that's read before ever being properly
attached. Kept as a real, defensible improvement regardless.
